---

<PageLayout
  title="PL-7737: the oral MC4R agonist aiming to be a pill for obesity"
  kicker="Investigational"
  description="PL-7737 is Palatin's investigational oral MC4R agonist — an attempt to do for the appetite receptor what dersimelagon did for the pigment receptor: turn an injected-peptide idea into a swallowable small molecule, for both common obesity and rare MC4R-pathway disease."
  updated="2026"
  about={[
    { name: 'PL-7737', type: 'Drug', sameAs: ['https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Melanocortin_4_receptor'] },
    { name: 'Melanocortin 4 receptor', type: 'MedicalEntity', sameAs: ['https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Melanocortin_4_receptor'] },
    { name: 'Obesity', type: 'MedicalCondition', sameAs: ['https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Obesity'] },
  ]}
>
  <KeyTakeaways
    items={[
      'PL-7737 is Palatin’s investigational oral MC4R agonist for obesity — a small molecule designed as a pill, not an injected peptide.',
      'It targets MC4R, the brain’s appetite rheostat — the same receptor as setmelanotide, but by mouth.',
      'It is aimed at both common obesity and rare MC4R-pathway disorders; it holds FDA Orphan Drug Designation for leptin-receptor-deficiency obesity.',
      'In preclinical models it drove weight loss and worked synergistically when combined with the GLP-1/GIP drug tirzepatide.',
      'It is early — strong preclinical data and first-in-human Phase 1 testing around 2026, not an approved drug.',
    ]}
  />

  <p>
    PL-7737 is Palatin's bet that the <a href="/receptors/mc4r">MC4R</a> appetite switch can
    be drugged with a pill. The approved MC4R agonist, <a href="/setmelanotide">setmelanotide</a>,
    is a daily injection; PL-7737 is a small molecule built to be swallowed instead — the same
    move <a href="/dersimelagon">dersimelagon</a> made for the pigment receptor, applied to the
    appetite one.<Cite n={1} />
  </p>

  <h2>An oral small molecule, not a peptide</h2>
  <p>
    The strategy here follows a pattern that recurs across the melanocortin pipeline. Peptides
    like setmelanotide must be injected, because a swallowed peptide is digested before it
    works. A <em>small molecule</em> can be engineered to survive the gut and be absorbed as a
    tablet — so PL-7737 aims to deliver MC4R activation in the most convenient possible form for
    a chronic condition like obesity.<Cite n={1} /> Convenience is not a footnote in obesity
    treatment; it shapes who will actually take a drug long-term.
  </p>

  <h2>Two markets in one molecule</h2>
  <p>
    PL-7737 is being positioned for two overlapping problems. The larger is
    <strong>common obesity</strong>, where preclinical work showed weight loss on its own and
    stronger results when combined with the GLP-1/GIP drug tirzepatide — echoing the
    combination logic Palatin is pursuing with
    <a href="/bremelanotide-tirzepatide">bremelanotide plus tirzepatide</a>.<Cite n={1} /> The
    other is <strong>rare MC4R-pathway disease</strong>: PL-7737 holds FDA Orphan Drug
    Designation for obesity caused by leptin-receptor (LEPR) deficiency,<Cite n={2} /> the same
    kind of upstream defect that setmelanotide treats. One oral molecule, aimed at both the mass
    market and the rare-disease niche.
  </p>

  <h2>Status</h2>
  <p>
    PL-7737 is early. As of 2026 it has strong preclinical efficacy data and orphan designation,
    with first-in-human Phase 1 single- and multiple-ascending-dose testing beginning around
    2026 and early clinical data expected to follow.<Cite n={3} /> Promising preclinical results
    are a starting line, not a finish; whether the oral MC4R approach translates to humans is
    exactly what those trials will test.
  </p>

  <h2>The honest bottom line</h2>
  <p>
    PL-7737 is one to watch rather than one to conclude on. If it works, it would make MC4R
    activation available as a pill and slot naturally into the emerging strategy of pairing
    melanocortin drugs with GLP-1s. If it doesn't, it will join the long list of appetite drugs
    that looked good in mice. For the receptor it targets, see
    <a href="/receptors/mc4r">MC4R</a>; for the combination idea, see
    <a href="/bremelanotide-tirzepatide">bremelanotide + tirzepatide</a>; for the whole field,
    the <a href="/pipeline">melanocortin pipeline</a>.
  </p>

  <div class="not-prose mt-8 rounded-lg border border-[var(--border)] bg-[var(--accent-soft)] p-6 text-sm leading-relaxed">
